00:00:01.620 --> 00:00:04.842
Prof: So the rules of
quantum mechanics are going to

00:00:04.842 --> 00:00:06.510
be stated for one last time.
 

00:00:06.510 --> 00:00:10.646
Now we're using the fact that
you've heard them over and over,

00:00:10.646 --> 00:00:13.630
it's going to be more compact
than before.

00:00:13.630 --> 00:00:17.170
So it's really the form of many
postulates, because it's a

00:00:17.170 --> 00:00:19.530
theory which is based on
experiment;

00:00:19.530 --> 00:00:21.280
it's not deduced by mathematics.
 

00:00:21.280 --> 00:00:23.840
You make up some postulates
that condense all the

00:00:23.840 --> 00:00:24.960
experimental facts.
 

00:00:24.960 --> 00:00:27.773
There are new mathematical
results you will need,

00:00:27.773 --> 00:00:29.180
but they are separate.
 

00:00:29.180 --> 00:00:31.580
They are deducible
mathematically.

00:00:31.580 --> 00:00:34.110
They are not part of the
physics postulates.

00:00:34.110 --> 00:00:39.288
The first postulate--by the
way, this is the postulate for

00:00:39.288 --> 00:00:40.560
Physics 201.
 

00:00:40.560 --> 00:00:42.721
If you know more mathematics
and so on, there's another way

00:00:42.721 --> 00:00:44.584
to write the postulate,
but we're not interested in

00:00:44.584 --> 00:00:44.920
that.
 

00:00:44.920 --> 00:00:47.350
We just want the rules for this
class,

00:00:47.350 --> 00:00:52.050
and I don't even care how much
of this you carry in your head,

00:00:52.050 --> 00:00:54.190
but I want you to know that in
principle,

00:00:54.190 --> 00:00:56.410
every problem I gave you,
every question I asked,

00:00:56.410 --> 00:01:00.450
can be answered just by turning
to these postulates,

00:01:00.450 --> 00:01:02.219
so you should know what they
are.

00:01:02.219 --> 00:01:05.700
So the first postulate is that
every particle--

00:01:05.700 --> 00:01:09.078
this is for 1 dimension,
1 particle only--

00:01:09.078 --> 00:01:10.950
is given by a certain wave
function,

00:01:10.950 --> 00:01:14.545
Y(x),
that contains all the possible

00:01:14.545 --> 00:01:16.819
information on that particle.
 

00:01:16.819 --> 00:01:20.292
This is the analog of x
and p in classical

00:01:20.292 --> 00:01:21.049
mechanics.
 

00:01:21.049 --> 00:01:26.677
And we always choose Y
so that Y^(2)dx is

00:01:26.677 --> 00:01:30.220
normalized to 1 in all of space.
 

00:01:30.220 --> 00:01:32.980
That is a convention;
it's not required.

00:01:32.980 --> 00:01:35.961
If you take a Y and you
multiply it by a number,

00:01:35.961 --> 00:01:38.170
it stands for the same physical
state.

00:01:38.170 --> 00:01:42.196
So you pick the number so that
the squared integral of Y

00:01:42.196 --> 00:01:42.959
is 1.
 

00:01:42.959 --> 00:01:52.190
The second thing is,
a state of definite momentum.

00:01:52.190 --> 00:01:54.535
In other words,
is there a wave function that

00:01:54.535 --> 00:01:57.893
describes a particle guaranteed
to have a definite momentum when

00:01:57.893 --> 00:01:58.800
I measure it?
 

00:01:58.800 --> 00:02:00.739
The answer is yes.
 

00:02:00.739 --> 00:02:04.890
That function is denoted by
Y _p(x).

00:02:04.890 --> 00:02:06.280
It is not an arbitrary function.
 

00:02:06.280 --> 00:02:09.080
This Y is whatever you
like.

00:02:09.080 --> 00:02:12.425
This is a particular Y
which assures you that if you

00:02:12.425 --> 00:02:15.080
measure my momentum when I'm in
this state,

00:02:15.080 --> 00:02:19.747
