00:43:50.780 --> 00:43:54.628
Identical particles in quantum
mechanics have very different

00:43:54.628 --> 00:43:57.826
connotations from identical
particles in classical

00:43:57.826 --> 00:43:58.739
mechanics.
 

00:43:58.739 --> 00:44:01.110
So in classical mechanics,
suppose you have identical

00:44:01.110 --> 00:44:01.750
twins, okay?
 

00:44:01.750 --> 00:44:04.250
They're born and they're
separated, they're moving

00:44:04.250 --> 00:44:04.710
around.
 

00:44:04.710 --> 00:44:07.119
Let's say they look identical
in every way.

00:44:07.119 --> 00:44:08.710
We can still follow them.
 

00:44:08.710 --> 00:44:11.050
We know this is Joe and this is
Moe.

00:44:11.050 --> 00:44:14.371
Follow the two characters no
matter how identical they are,

00:44:14.371 --> 00:44:17.179
because we can keep track of
them continuously.

00:44:17.179 --> 00:44:21.146
So let's do the following
experiment involving these

00:44:21.146 --> 00:44:21.768
twins.
 

00:44:21.768 --> 00:44:26.188
There are 4 doors in this room
and 1 twin comes out like this,

00:44:26.188 --> 00:44:28.869
the other twin comes out like
that.

00:44:28.869 --> 00:44:31.070
Then they do one of 2 things.
 

00:44:31.070 --> 00:44:37.858
Either they cross over like
this, or this guy goes back to

00:44:37.858 --> 00:44:43.219
that door, that guy goes back to
this door.

00:44:43.219 --> 00:44:46.099
Now suppose you saw them
running like this in the

00:44:46.099 --> 00:44:48.746
beginning,
and you left the room when this

00:44:48.746 --> 00:44:51.407
was happening,
and you saw them enter these 2

00:44:51.407 --> 00:44:53.871
doors,
you cannot tell which of the 2

00:44:53.871 --> 00:44:55.920
happened,
because you've just got 2

00:44:55.920 --> 00:44:58.539
identical twins and these 2
identical exit doors.

00:44:58.539 --> 00:45:00.059
But somebody knows what happens.
 

00:45:00.059 --> 00:45:02.932
Somebody in that room who was
watching them can clearly tell

00:45:02.932 --> 00:45:05.903
you, if this happened or that
happened, because you can follow

00:45:05.903 --> 00:45:07.219
the twins at all times.
 

00:45:07.219 --> 00:45:09.219
So even though they're
identical, they're

00:45:09.219 --> 00:45:10.119
distinguishable.
 

00:45:10.119 --> 00:45:14.039
They cannot swap roles without
your knowing.

00:45:14.039 --> 00:45:18.128
But imagine now that these are
not classical particles but

00:45:18.128 --> 00:45:20.710
quantum particles,
like electrons.

00:45:20.710 --> 00:45:22.994
For an electron,
you don't have a definite

00:45:22.994 --> 00:45:24.500
location or a trajectory.
 

00:45:24.500 --> 00:45:26.340
You only have probabilities.
 

00:45:26.340 --> 00:45:29.519
So you know an electron was
emitted here and emitted here,

00:45:29.519 --> 00:45:32.199
and later on was absorbed here
and absorbed here,

00:45:32.199 --> 00:45:34.710
and you cannot tell who really
came here.

00:45:34.710 --> 00:45:36.820
Was it this guy or was it that
guy?

00:45:36.820 --> 00:45:40.159
There's no way to tell.
 

00:45:40.159 --> 00:45:43.144
So when you have identical
particles whose trajectories you

00:45:43.144 --> 00:45:45.586
cannot follow,
when you catch a particle here

00:45:45.586 --> 00:45:48.635
and a particle there,
you cannot say Joe was here and

00:45:48.635 --> 00:45:49.530
Moe was there.
 

00:45:49.530 --> 00:45:51.458
It's not allowed,
because you're not following

00:45:51.458 --> 00:45:52.059
their names.
 

00:45:52.059 --> 00:45:54.304
You can only say,
"I found a particle here,

00:45:54.304 --> 00:45:55.880
I found a particle there."
 

00:45:55.880 --> 00:45:59.601
Therefore the theory cannot
give different probabilities for

00:45:59.601 --> 00:46:02.630
finding particle 1 here and
particle 2 there,

00:46:02.630 --> 00:46:04.369
and particle 2 there and
particle 1 here,

00:46:04.369 --> 00:46:07.239
because the outcomes are
indistinguishable,

00:46:07.239 --> 00:46:10.150
so the probabilities must be
equal.

00:46:10.150 --> 00:46:12.597
So for 2 identical
particles, p (x_1

00:46:12.597 --> 00:46:15.197
x_2) must =
p( x_2

00:46:15.197 --> 00:46:16.369
x_1).
 

00:46:16.369 --> 00:46:20.380
That's not true for these
functions.

00:46:20.380 --> 00:46:24.980
Now I'll write a function for
